## 1. Purpose
This policy defines what events [COMPANY] logs, how logs are centralized and protected, how long they are retained, and how they are monitored and alerted on — so that security events are detected and investigated, and so that **access to PHI is auditable** as required by HIPAA (45 CFR § 164.312(b)).

## 2. Scope
Applies to all in-scope systems: the SaaS application, [AWS] accounts/services, [Snowflake], databases/[RDS], CI/CD ([GitHub Actions]), and endpoints, plus the logging and monitoring infrastructure itself. It covers security, audit, and operational logs, with special handling for PHI-access audit logs.

## 3. Policy
1. Security-relevant events **shall** be logged on all in-scope systems (§5), including **all access to PHI** with sufficient detail to answer who accessed what record, when, from where, and what action was taken.
2. Logs **shall** be centralized to a dedicated, access-restricted [log-archive] account/store and **shall not** be alterable by the systems or accounts that generate them.
3. Logs **shall** be protected for **integrity and confidentiality**: stored encrypted (`cryptography-and-key-management.md.template`), made **immutable** (e.g., **S3 Object Lock / WORM**) for the retention period, and access to logs restricted to authorized roles and itself logged.
4. **Logs shall not contain PHI or secrets in plaintext** beyond the minimum identifiers needed for audit; application logs **shall** avoid logging full PHI payloads.
5. Logs **shall** be retained for [≥ 12 months readily searchable, with archival to satisfy the HIPAA 6-year documentation requirement where the log constitutes required documentation] — see §6.
6. Time **shall** be synchronized (NTP) across systems so log timestamps are reliable and correlatable.
7. Alerts **shall** be defined for high-risk events (§7), routed to [on-call/SOC], triaged, and escalated to incident response (`../resilience/incident-response-plan.md.template`) where warranted.
8. Logs and access-review reports **shall** be reviewed at defined intervals (`../access/access-control-policy.md.template` for periodic access reviews), and PHI-access logs reviewed/audited per §6.

## 4. Roles & Responsibilities
| Role | Responsibility |
|---|---|
| [Security Officer] | Owns this policy; defines logging scope, alerts, and retention; oversees log review. |
| [Platform Engineering Lead] | Implements log pipelines, centralization, immutability, and retention controls. |
| [On-call / SOC] | Monitors alerts; triages and escalates security events. |
| Service Owners | Ensure their systems emit required logs and avoid logging PHI/secrets. |
| [CTO] | Approves this policy. |

See `../governance/roles-and-responsibilities.md.template` for full role definitions.

## 5. What to Log
| Source | Logs |
|---|---|
| [AWS] control plane | **CloudTrail** (management + data events for S3/[sensitive] buckets), org-wide, all regions, to log-archive account. |
| AWS threat detection | **GuardDuty** findings; **Security Hub** aggregated findings/standards. |
| Network | VPC Flow Logs, [WAF] logs, load balancer access logs (`network-security-policy.md.template`). |
| Application | Authn/authz events, admin actions, **PHI access (record-level audit)**, errors; no plaintext PHI/secrets. |
| Database / [RDS] | Connection, auth, and (where supported) query/audit logs. |
| **Snowflake** | **ACCESS_HISTORY** and account-usage views (queries, objects/columns accessed) exported for PHI-access auditing. |
| CI/CD | [GitHub] audit log, workflow run logs, deployment records (`change-management-policy.md.template`). |
| Endpoints | EDR/MDM events (`endpoint-security-policy.md.template`). |

Each event should capture: timestamp (synced), identity/principal, source, action, target/object, and outcome.

## 6. Retention & Immutability
1. Logs **shall** be written to immutable storage ([S3 with Object Lock in compliance mode] / WORM) for the retention period; deletion before expiry **shall not** be possible by operational roles.
2. Operational/security logs are retained [≥ 12 months online + [N] years archived]; logs that constitute **HIPAA required documentation** are retained **at least 6 years** (45 CFR § 164.316(b)(2)).
3. PHI-access audit logs **shall** be retained to support investigations, accounting-of-disclosures, and breach determinations (`../healthcare/hipaa-breach-notification-procedure.md.template`).

## 7. Monitoring & Alerting
Alerts **shall** be configured for at least: root/privileged account use, IAM/policy changes, disabling of logging or [AWS Config], GuardDuty/Security Hub high/critical findings, anomalous PHI access or bulk data export (incl. [Snowflake] large/unusual queries), failed-auth spikes, secret detections, and changes to security groups exposing resources. Alerts route to [on-call/SOC] with defined response SLAs and feed incident response.

## 8. Exceptions
Exceptions to this policy require documented risk acceptance per `../governance/exceptions-and-waivers.md.template`, approved by the [Security Officer], time-bound, and recorded in the exceptions log. Disabling or reducing logging on an in-scope system requires such an exception.

## 9. Compliance, Monitoring & Enforcement
Compliance is verified by confirming log coverage, immutability/retention configuration, alert effectiveness, and log-review records during internal audit and management review. Tampering with or disabling logs is a serious violation handled per `../people/hr-security-policy.md.template` and investigated per `../resilience/incident-response-plan.md.template`.

